{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01MuuEYsw4FvqRKr7Q9WzphV","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is a test planning task for a content moderation service. I need to analyze 6 behaviors and determine the minimum test infrastructure level needed to catch real failures for each one.\n\nLet me go through each behavior systematically:\n\n## Behavior 1: Image with explicit content is flagged and held for review, not published\n\nThe key failure modes:\n- The image classification (AI model) incorrectly passes a flagged image\n- The flagging logic doesn't work properly\n- The post is published despite being flagged\n- The post isn't held for review\n\nMOCK-MISS: Could a pure in-process mock miss this? \n- If I mock the vision model to return \"explicit=true\", I could verify the downstream logic works\n- BUT: the real failure is \"the vision model classified this as explicit, but our system published it anyway\"\n- A mock of the vision model can verify we handle the signal correctly, but the real failure is: what if the real vision model gives a different output?\n- Actually, for THIS behavior, the failure is: \"explicit content should be flagged\". The vision model's classification IS the ground truth we're testing against.\n\nREAL-INFRA: Does it depend on OS, real network, or subprocess?\n- Yes! It depends on calling the real AI vision model (real external API)\n- This is a network/external API call\n\nLLM-DEP: Does correctness depend on what a real LLM produces?\n- YES. The vision model must correctly classify the image as explicit\n- A mock could verify the \"if flagged, hold it\" logic, but it can't verify \"the vision model will actually flag this explicit image\"\n- This is an Agentic-level dependency\n\nMOCK-HIDE: Would mocking hide a real failure?\n- Yes! If I mock the vision model, I could pass all the tests but fail in production because the real model doesn't classify the image as explicit\n\nSo the minimum level is **Agentic** — we need the real vision model to verify that explicit images are actually classified as explicit.\n\n\nThe distinction between System and Agentic matters here: System-level tests might stub external APIs through the test framework, but Agentic-level tests require the actual AI model producing real classification outputs. Since the correctness depends on how the real vision model handles image compression, model versions, and other variables, this requires **Agentic** infrastructure.\n\n## Behavior 2: Text post with hate speech is flagged regardless of obfuscation\n\nMOCK-MISS: Could a mock miss this?\n- A mock could verify \"if the text model returns hate=true, we flag it\"\n- But the real failure is: \"our text model fails to detect obfuscated hate speech\"\n- The mock won't expose gaps in the model's ability to handle obfuscation\n\nLLM-DEP: Real LLM produces different outputs\n- Different models handle obfuscation differently\n- The same obfuscated text should consistently get classified the same way, but this depends entirely on the real model's training\n\nREAL-INFRA: External API?\n- Yes, calls the real text classification model\n\nMOCK-HIDE: Would mocking hide real failures?\n- Absolutely. A mock would accept whatever you tell it to return\n\nMinimum level: **Agentic** — we need the real text model to verify it catches obfuscated hate speech.\n\n## Behavior 3: Post passing both checks is published, not held or dropped\n\nMOCK-MISS: Could a mock miss this?\n- Yes\n\n. If I mock both the vision and text models to return \"pass\", I can verify the publish logic works when both checks pass. But the real failure modes are: the post gets held even though both checks pass, the post gets silently dropped, or publishing fails entirely. These are orchestration logic errors, not model accuracy issues. With good mocks of both models, I can test whether the system correctly publishes when given the OK signal from both. The real question is whether the post actually gets published—this likely involves writing to a database or posting to a queue/API.\n\nIf publishing means writing to a database, I might need a real database. If it's calling an API, I'd need a real API or at least a system-level test. Mocking the vision model, text model, and publish destination together could hide real failures like a broken publish API, a down database, or network errors. The behavior I'm testing is about decision logic, not availability, so I think the minimum viable approach is integration-level testing: real connections to verify the post reaches the publish destination, but mocked AI models since the behavior is about routing, not model functionality. Though I should reconsider whether unit-level testing with good mocks could be sufficient here.\n\nThe core failure I'm trying to catch is posts being silently dropped or not published when they should be. A mock publish destination could hide this if the mock accepts everything but the real API rate-limits us or fails in production. That means I need a real (or test) database and publish destination to catch the actual failure boundary, though I don't need real AI models or to test their accuracy. I'll go with integration-level testing for this one.\n\nFor the pipeline timing requirement, I need to check whether mocking could miss latency issues.\n\nIf I mock the AI models to return instantly, I'd pass the latency test but fail in production since real models take 1-3 seconds each. The real failure depends on actual API calls to the vision and text models—network latency is part of the SLA. I'm testing latency itself, not model correctness, so I need real calls to get realistic timing. A mock returning in 10ms would pass a 5-second SLA test but fail in production. This requires system-level testing with real external API calls to catch the actual latency behavior. The latency result depends on real AI/ML model calls, so there's an argument for Agentic. But I'm focused on measuring performance through the full pipeline rather than model behavior variation. The test needs real API calls to capture actual latency, which makes System the minimum level. Agentic would apply if the outcome itself varied based on model non-determinism, but here I'm testing an SLA constraint, not model accuracy.\n\nFor Behavior 5, when the vision model becomes unavailable, requests should queue instead of failing immediately.\n\nA mock could simulate the API throwing an exception, but the real risk is whether that exception gets silently swallowed and the post gets auto-approved anyway. I can test the retry queuing logic at Integration or Unit level by injecting a failure condition. The key failure mode—silently approving when the API is down—would surface if I verify the exception handling path properly.\n\nFor Unit testing, I'd mock both the vision model to throw an exception and the queue mechanism itself, then assert that `queue.add()` gets called on failure. For Integration testing, I'd want a real queue or a test double that behaves like one, since the actual queueing behavior matters more than the mock. The question is whether a full in-memory queue in tests would hide production failures like a full queue—but that's a separate concern from the core logic of \"exception → queue instead of auto-approve.\"\n\nThe minimum is probably **Unit** with a faithful queue mock, since the failure mode is straightforward: the vision model fails, and the post should be queued, not approved. A mock queue that tracks calls would catch this. Integration testing adds value only if we're concerned about queue implementation details, which we're not here. is a Unit test—we're testing one method in isolation with mocks, passing data as arguments and checking outputs. The retry queue is mocked, not a real queue, so there's no actual I/O happening.\n\nBut the original concern was whether the retry logic itself works correctly when the queue is real. A Unit test won't catch if the queue implementation has a bug or if the post_id isn't being stored properly. An Integration test would wire the actual retry queue module together with the moderation service and verify the full flow: exception raised, post added to queue, queue persists it. That's where I'd catch real failures in the integration between these components. The failure happens in the retry mechanism. For Behavior 6, I'm checking whether moderation decisions stay consistent when the same image is submitted multiple times.\n\nThe vision model needs to be called repeatedly with identical input, and it should classify the image the same way each time. This requires actual API calls since the behavior depends on how the real model responds. A mock would always return the same deterministic result, potentially hiding cases where the actual model produces different classifications on subsequent calls—whether due to non-determinism, caching behavior, or other runtime factors. Since correctness hinges on the real model's actual behavior across multiple invocations, this needs System or Integration level testing. but the core issue is the vision model's accuracy in classification, not the integration itself. Since the behavior hinges on whether the real vision model correctly identifies explicit content, this is fundamentally an Agentic concern—testing the model's actual classification capability rather than system connectivity. The distinction between System and Agentic here is that System would verify an external API call works, while Agentic specifically validates the model's decision-making. Given that the test's success depends entirely on the vision model's real output, Agentic is the appropriate minimum level.\n\nFor the second behavior around obfuscated hate speech, the same principle applies—the real text model must demonstrate it can recognize disguised harmful content, making this an Agentic test. The third behavior shifts focus to testing whether the orchestration logic correctly publishes posts that pass both checks, which requires real connections to the publishing system but not the AI models themselves, placing it at Integration level. The real failure we're trying to prevent matters here. A logic bug where the post gets held despite passing both checks is catchable at Unit level, but the behavior says \"published\" — meaning it actually reaches the publishing system. That requires Integration testing to verify the publish call succeeds, not just that it's invoked.\n\nFor the latency behavior, we need real API calls to the vision and text models to get meaningful measurements. Mocking would give false confidence about actual performance, so System testing is the minimum viable approach.\n\nI'm reconsidering whether Agentic applies here. While real model calls are involved, the distinction is that System covers infrastructure properties like latency and network behavior, whereas Agentic specifically tests AI/ML non-determinism or multi-model interactions. Since we're measuring an infrastructure property rather than model behavior, System is more fitting.\n\nWhen the vision model becomes unavailable, we need to verify the post gets queued for retry rather than auto-approved. A Unit test with mocks could catch the logic error, but Integration testing confirms the retry queue actually receives and stores the post. Integration is the minimum level to catch real failures in the queueing mechanism itself.\n\nFor borderline image decisions, we need the actual vision model to reveal whether it's consistent across multiple calls. Only the real model can expose non-determinism or inconsistency in its outputs, making Agentic the appropriate minimum level.\n\nNow I'm drafting test descriptions for each behavior at their minimum required levels and checking alignment with the overall testing strategy.\n\nBehavior 1 tests whether explicit content gets properly held for review by verifying the vision model's classification and the system's handling of flagged content. Behavior 2 validates that obfuscated hate speech is caught despite letter substitution and unicode lookalikes, checking the text model's robustness against evasion techniques. Both tests are consistent with the plan since they exercise the real models' actual capabilities rather than mocking them.\n\nBehavior 3 ensures posts passing both checks actually get published to their destination rather than being held or silently dropped—this is primarily an integration-level concern since it validates the orchestration between the two moderation checks and the publish mechanism. Behavior 4 measures end-to-end latency across the full pipeline using real API calls to both models, confirming the system completes within 5 seconds. Behavior 5 addresses what happens when the vision model becomes unavailable, testing the system's resilience and fallback behavior.\n\nWhen the vision model fails, posts should be queued for retry instead of auto-approved. This requires testing with a real retry queue to verify the failure-handling logic works correctly. Behavior 6 examines whether the vision model produces consistent classifications for borderline images when submitted multiple times in quick succession, which can only be validated against the actual model since its behavior near decision boundaries is inherently non-deterministic. The failure mode here is publishing instead of queueing when the vision model fails. A unit test with mocked dependencies can verify the code calls `queue.add()` rather than `publish()` when `classify()` throws an exception.\n\nHowever, \"queued for retry\" suggests more than just the decision logic—it implies the queue actually persists the post and enables retries later. That distinction pushes toward Integration level, where I'd verify the queue system genuinely stores and retrieves the post. The Unit test catches the immediate branching logic, but Integration catches whether the queueing mechanism itself works end-to-end. that verifies persistence.\n\nMy confidence levels for behavior 5 reflect that Integration is likely the minimum—around 65% probability—since we need to verify the post actually persists in the queue. Unit testing with mocks could work in some cases (25%), but System, Agentic, and Workflow levels are less probable (5%, 2%, 3% respectively). I should also verify that the test description aligns with the minimum level I've identified.\n\nChecking each behavior's consistency: Behavior 1 requires the actual vision model to classify explicit images, so Agentic is appropriate. Behavior 2 needs the real text model to identify obfuscated hate speech, confirming Agentic. Behavior 3 demands a real publish destination to verify the post actually goes live, making Integration necessary. Behavior 4 measures end-to-end latency with genuine API calls, requiring System-level testing. Behavior 5 needs a real queue to confirm persistence, validating Integration. Behavior 6 tests whether the vision model returns consistent classifications on borderline images, requiring Agentic access.\n\nAll six behaviors align with their assigned test levels. The justifications explain why each level is minimal: mocking would mask real failures in model performance, external system integration, or infrastructure behavior that only surface in production.\n\nFor explicit content detection, the vision model's classification capability can't be verified with mocks—only real inference reveals training data issues, preprocessing failures, or model drift. For obfuscated hate speech, the text model must handle actual adversarial techniques like character substitution and unicode lookalikes, which mocks bypass entirely. Publishing success requires a real destination to confirm posts reach the system rather than just executing the publish call. Latency measurement demands genuine API calls since mocks hide actual bottlenecks and would never trigger the 5-second SLA violation. Rate limiting needs real concurrent requests to expose synchronization bugs or resource exhaustion. Finally, end-to-end recovery testing requires actual infrastructure failures to validate the system's resilience without mocking away the real failure modes. differences in model versioning, inference randomness, or caching behavior. A mock would mask non-determinism by always returning identical results, so I need the actual vision model. Testing at the agentic level captures real LLM behavior variation without requiring a multi-step workflow.\n\nThe behavior IDs and descriptions are: explicit content in images gets flagged for review rather than published; hate speech in text posts is caught even with obfuscation; posts cleared by both checks proceed to publication; the full moderation pipeline executes within 5 seconds; and vision model failures trigger a retry queue instead of auto-approving content.\n\nFor borderline image classifications, I'm checking whether the same submission produces consistent decisions across multiple runs.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13375,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13375},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2209acc5-7850-4bec-9de3-2764cd21ac12","uuid":"14708ecf-e80a-4fcc-88f0-6d0a545abf83"}
